Getting the audio routing setup right took me a bit of time and playing around with settings, so I thought it might be fun to share. I wanted to get a few things out of this&hellip;
Playing the piano just by itself should work without any hassle I should be able to monitor the piano and listen to videos through the same headset/speakers I should be able to set up virtual instrument plugins for DAWs on my computer, play them with the keyboard, and monitor everything through the same headset/speakers The setup None of this was ultimately too complicated but there were a few tricks to get it working just right. Here&rsquo;s a basic diagram of the physical setup below.
p i a n o b l u e t o o t u o h a h s n e m b b a p o d a s r e d t c o s s i m p t p p e a a u a n d t k d e e a r r l s o n e s p e a k e r s The piano sits at 90Â° to my desk, so it was easy enough to run a long USB cable directly into the back of my computer and leave it there. I think it may be more common for people to set this up with a laptop but I like having a permanent setup with my desktop computer.
OK, so with this setup a few things work out of the box&hellip;
Bluetooth connection on the FP-30x has 2 modes - audio or MIDI. I&rsquo;m almost always connecting with audio to listen to videos or a backing track. Adjusting the volume on the ipad lets me adjust the relative levels to the piano and the piano volume effectively becomes the master
